it is by ambiguity that... Sartre... fundamentally defined man, that being whose being is not to be, that subjectivity which realizes itself only as a presence in the world.... a being who makes himself a lack of being in order that there might be being.












Although scientists have traditionally denounced metaphor as imprecise rhetorical embellishment... Ted Brown [notes] “Metaphorical reasoning is ''at the very core'' of what scientists do when they design experiments, make discoveries, formulate theories and models, and describe their results to others.” ... <br /> <br />Metaphoric ambiguity may actually be a fertile source of inquiry, and metaphors may allow leaps beyond stabilized meanings ... revolutionize the process of scientific exploration. Science is //built// on metaphorical foundations, so metaphors occur in much of the science we hear about every day. Thus, we require greater sensitivity to their presence and implications.

… //Yawe//— the animate to be. I am, you are, s/he is. To speak of those possessed with life and spirit we must say //yawe//. By what linguistic confluence do //Yahweh// of the Old Testament and //yawe// of the New World both fall from the mouths of the reverent? Isn’t this just what it means, to be, to have the breath of life within, to be the offspring of Creation? The language reminds us, in every sentence, of our kinship with all of the animate world.

Rest (1973) [showed] that students prefer the highest stage of reasoning they comprehend but that they do not comprehend more than one stage above their own. As a result, assimilation of reasoning occurs primarily when it is the next  stage up from the student’s level. Developmental moral discussion thus arouses cognitive-moral conflict and exposes students to reasoning by other students at the next stage above their own.






<$details open="yes" class="notification" summary="Making a TiddlyWiki for quotes? How to build it so it scales well: ">

<$details open="yes" class="notification" summary="Plan to make one tiddler for each excerpt">

<<<.index-right
{{Never Type the Same Quote Twice}}
<<< —  {{Never Type the Same Quote Twice!!author}} <br />[[(liberally paraphrased)|https://www.cambiaresearch.com/articles/77/rule-3---never-write-the-same-code-twice#:~:text=Never%20is%20a%20Strong%20Word,begins%20with%20the%20word%20never.&text=Situations%20such%20as%20this%20are,rule%20sparingly%2C%20but%20without%20shame.]]

; Why? 
: Think of each tiddler as an index card, something you might want to take in your pocket while leaving related things behind. This will allow you to access quotes flexibly as the project grows.
:: //(Except this is a ''magical'' index card: it can simultaneously be part of multiple stacks, and morph its appearance with the wave of a css wand!)//

;What goes in the "body" area of the tiddler?
: Just the words from your source
* (Everything else (author, bibliographic source, page-location, notes) belongs in special ''fields'' — more on those soon...)
* (Don't panic if you initially find yourself with other key info jammed in there; you can decide over time whether this or that merits a field, and clean up as needed.)
; How much text should I put into one tiddler?
:Usually just the sentence or paragraph (or dialogue-exchange, etc.) that's "quotable" (relative to your purposes).
: (Don't panic if you find yourself with strings of quotes hastily pasted into one tiddler, but aim to parcel them out when you get a chance. Of course, there are tools for that, too. ;) )
; How should these little tiddlers be titled?
: Good question! 
:It actually doesn't matter much for now, as long as the title is unique. 
:: You could title it with a concise descriptive teaser, or with a quick string that abbreviates the title and page. (Add flibble's relink plugin to make internal links less fragile if you tinker with your names later.)
; How about an example?
: [[Aristotle considers three lives]]
: [[inner vs outer]]
; It sounds like each quote is so much work!
: No need to re-enter all the details about the source each time!
:{{$:/core/images/clone-button}}Just ''clone'' the first tiddler once it's set up for the source you're currently reading.
: (We can consider other time-saving tips later for the input process. The focus now is structure.)
</$details>

<$details open="yes" class="notification" summary="Make one tiddler for each book (or article / anthology chapter, whatever)">

*Within that source tiddler, you'll have an automatically-''filtered list'' (or a table) of all the excerpts from that source. 
* Example: [[Aristotle, Nicomachean Ethics]]
*I recommend [[Shiraz|$:/plugins/kookma/shiraz]] dynamic tables to display a table that selects tiddlers based on a filter and can be sorted and adjusted on the fly. BUT you can also just use a filtered list function to transclude all the excerpts that belong to the book/text-source. 
*Once you're comfortable with filtered lists, you can set up other "slices" — filtering based on [[education]], for example.
</$details>
<$details open="yes" class="notification" summary="Tips for understanding fields">

; What are fields, and how do I work with them?
: A field is a "cubbyhole" (or a labeled fill-in-the-blank) for information of a specific kind. 
* Usually ~TiddlyWiki fields are created, and appear, only in edit mode. Find the field creation and editing controls below the body of each tiddler...
* {{$:/plugins/kookma/utility/images/view-fields.svg}}Click the "Show fields" toggle control near the top of the sidebar... Now if you navigate back to the example tiddlers, you can see fields even while browsing. 
;''Use clearly-named fields for all metadata''
*Any informational parameter that has data structure that you might want to format or rearrange down the road should be given its own field.
* Be careful not to use TW's own special-purpose fields. (Alas, "source" and "title" are taken, for example. So are "type" and "name".) 
* Field names cannot contain spaces, but they can contain dashes or underscores, so `source-text` works. 
* An automatic list of fields in use is under the hood in each TiddlyWiki. Find it here: [[$:/snippets/allfields]]
</$details>
<$details open="yes" class="notification" summary="Play with how content is displayed">

; How can [[ViewTemplate|$:/tags/ViewTemplate]] customizations help me display field data?

* I've added [[a line under the subtitle|$:/springer/source-info]] to specify source information (as contained in the relevant fields)
* I've also added an element near the bottom of the [[ViewTemplate|$:/tags/ViewTemplate]] to [[display notes|$:/springer/add-notes-below]] (from a ''notes'' field) if there are any...

; How can I add style, color, and graphics?

:Add something like this stylesheet spec: [[excerpt-style]]
:* Notice that it contains special block-quote css. A million variations are possible, but one of them is on display at [[education]].
:* This site also uses [[$:/LinkStyle/Stylesheet]] to enable links to appear with icons or labels (as you see in the sidebar's Recent tab). Peek into the fields area for a tiddler to see how the details work!
</$details>
</$details>

<hr>
This demo tiddler will next offer an overview of all the tiddlers here that are tagged: <<tag excerpt>>.

<<table-dynamic filter:"[has[page]]" fields:"tbl-expand author text-title page title notes tbl-clone tbl-delete" sortOp:"nsort" stateTiddler:"excerpt overview list" sort:page class:"w-100 thead-dark" caption:"''Click any column header to sort. Preview row content with @@.tcr ''﹥'' @@ at left.''">>

:^^Note: This tiddler uses <mark>dynamic tables</mark> from [[$:/plugins/kookma/shiraz]] to organize information about excerpts. Other approaches, like using "table of contents" macro, are possible without plugins, but they're less flexible.^^

:^^If your project grows very large, such a catch-all location will become unwieldy. You'll instead find uses for cross-source slices (all excerpts, from any source, with [[education]], for example).^^

A dynamic table can include any desired combination of fields, and you can add a dynamic table to any tiddler (even adding one to custom ViewTemplate formats so that authors or texts automatically get their own dynamic tables). Not only can a dynamic table be sorted on the fly, but both the meta-data field contents and the content itself can be edited on the fly using the little "edit" icon at the upper left of the table area.

<$details summary="Advanced experimentation">

It's preferable not to overwrite shadow tiddlers, since changes made to a tiddlywiki file in this way will not carry over when the core is updated. 

However, overwriting a shadow tiddler can be a good way to learn.

Currently, two shadow tiddlers have been overwritten to allow the caption field to be displayed (where it's available) instead of the title. Those two overwritten shadow tiddlers are:

[[$:/core/macros/timeline]]
[[$:/core/ui/ViewTemplate/title]]

In each case, the pivotal invocation of the title field was replaced by:

`<$transclude field="caption">{{!!title}}</$transclude>`

</$details>

Now each man judges well the things he knows, and of these he is a good judge. And so the man who has been educated in a subject is a good judge of that subject, and the man who has received an all-round education is a good judge in general . Hence a young man is not a proper hearer of lectures on political science; for he is inexperienced in the actions that occur in life, but its discussions start from these and are about these; and, further, since he tends to follow his passions, his study will be vain and unprofitable, because the end aimed at is not knowledge but action.
